MATCH_TOOL: Edit|Write
MATCH_PATTERN: cartridges/games/(color-sort|stacker|the-split|[^/]*puzzle[^/]*)/[^/]+Renderer\.tsx
ADVISORY: |
  Pickup-and-place puzzle games (pick an item, animate it, drop into
  a target) should use a POP-ON-PICKUP ownership model, not a defer-
  until-settle model.

  Correct model:
    pickupFromTube(i):
      const ball = tubes[i].pop();          // ← POP immediately
      floating = { color: ball, fromTube: i, phase: 'lifting', ... };

    tryPlaceInto(dest):
      floating.fromTube = -(dest + 1);       // encode dest as negative
      floating.phase = 'traveling';
      selected = -1;                         // ← reset selection

    // On fall-settle (in loop):
      const destTube = -floating.fromTube - 1;
      tubes[destTube].push(floating.color);
      floating = null;

    dropSelected (cancel):
      floating.fromTube = -(home + 1);       // cancel also travels+falls
      floating.phase = 'traveling';
      selected = -1;

  Why: if pickup doesn't pop, the source still contains the ball
  during animation. When settle runs push() on destination, the ball
  DUPLICATES. Also `selected` never resets, so the gold-glow outline
  persists after placement.

  Related stale-logic trap: if pickup pops on day 1, ANY draw-time
  skip like `if (isSel && j === tubes[i].length - 1 && floating) continue;`
  was written for the non-pop era and MUST be deleted. After pop, that
  condition skips the ball UNDER the picked one (which is now the top
  of the shortened array) — the ball visually disappears until settle.

  Rule of thumb: if your `floating` ball variable owns the ball, the
  source array should NOT contain it. Never have both references
  simultaneously.
